This place is not crowded during weekdays which makes it a peaceful visit. Not many people around so we can enjoy the flowers and also take as many pictures as possible without much interruptions. Parking options are also closeby.<//review>

< text>
It's mid March. The Tulips have started blooming. The garden has mostly yellow tulips and few red ones. The garden looks very picturesque along with the windmill beside. Great place to spend an evening and to capture loads of pictures.
There is ample street parking and few mins walk to the beach.<//text>

If you like tulips you have to go. They are in full bloom. It's beautiful. You can walk around the planted area and enjoy the flowers or sit on the grass and have a picnic. There are a few benches as well. Really a beautiful place.  Parking is available but it get crowded.< /text>

<rate>4</rate><Text>With all the beautiful flowers and the windmill here, this place makes for a great photo-op! This garden is nice for bringing a blanket or chairs and just sitting and relaxing in either the shade or the sun. That's great for if you're a local, but for a visitor, which was my case, this is a good little area of Golden Gate Park to stop and look at for about 20 or so minutes and then keep going.  It's not too large so for me, I walked through the garden, took photos, walked around the windmill, and then sat on one of the many benches for a few minutes and then was on my way. Just as a quick heads-up for a visitor who's not that familiar with the locations of things in Golden Gate Park, this located within walking distance of Park Chalet Garden Restaurant and Ocean Beach.<//Text><pics>None< /pics><resp>None</resp><Gmap_id>0x808587b97c4ad097:0xf1ce4042d68b2b5<//Gmap_id></record>

< Review>
A pretty place to hang out. I'm Dutch, so I couldn't resist to visit this part of the park that is named after one of our former Queens. It's nice to stroll around a bit. Especially with all those tulips and a windmill.

It's not a place you would spend much time at. I wouldn't take the effort to go visit this part of the park for the sake of it. But if you're in the neighbourhood, why not.<//Review>

<username>Sarah Stierch< /username>< time>

< rating>
5</rating>
<Review>I've eaten at Oso a million times at this point and it's one of the most consistent restaurants in Sonoma Valley! Not only does Chef Dave have a dedicated, friendly staff, but he's cultivated a cult of locals who love dining at the bar or on the patio (like me!).

My favorite dishes include hummus (with amazing bread), shrimp cocktail, ceviche, shrimp & grits, and seasonal salads.

They also are extremely accommodating. Vegetarian dishes can be made vegan, for example.

Also the bartenders are great. While Oso has a small wine list, it features a lot of small production, hyper local sustainable wines. They also have great cocktails - the Blood Orange Margarita is one of the best drinks in the region.

OSO also shares my same values of inclusivity, celebrating diversity, and supporting democratic values. These are all things I look for when I'm considering where I'd like to spend my hard earned money!< /Review><pics>None< /pics>< Resp>
None< /Resp>

< rate>

<Text>3.5 stars rounded up to 4. We had a pleasant date night at Oso.

We shared a bunch of small plates, like burrata, broccolini, and deviled eggs. They were somewhat hit or miss - the burrata was the star of the show, with a large, creamy portion complemented by ripe tomatoes and brightened by vinegar. The broccolini was good, not great. It was more like chopped florets than broccolini, but the chick peas and parm were a nice touch. The deviled eggs were huge, though mostly flavorless.

The ambiance and enough of the food was good that I'd come back!</Text>< pictures>

< username>
John Johnson< /username>
< Date>
1487328599248< /Date>
< Review>
This superior restaurant and bar on the square in Sonoma, CA is a must visit.

I arrived during their Happy Hour (M-Th beginning at 5) and was greeted by the hostess, a server and the bartender, Rob. Talk about feeling welcome!

I selected a Syrah and decided to start with their Dungeness Crab Deviled Eggs. The house made yellow curry paste with a touch of paprika really made these a stand out.

Next up, I went for a fresh oyster tour. Two west coasters: Fanny Bay from British Columbia, A Capital Gen from WA, and the east coast New Brunswick Beausoleil. Tamari mignonette spiced nicely and topped with a jalape√±o slice floater along with what a sweet ketchup base cocktail sauce. All too notch-though not big-flavorful oysters.

My main course was one of the night's specials-a New York Strip Ramen!  A wonderfully rich full flavored broth! The noodles are cooked in the broth which is dark and hearty, an abundance of relatively thin sliced New York strip steak, sliced and quartered shiitake mushrooms, daikon radish greens and thinly sliced Easter radish round out this flavor champion dish.

You need to dine (and drink) at Oso! The staff, with their unobtrusive casual friendliness, compliment both the food and atmosphere. I will, without a doubt, dine here again!< /Review>

< Review>
Chef David Bush is a genius! Who'd thought deviled eggs could taste so mind blowing? The whole night was on point. The service was great, Kudos to the amazing and energetic manager and our lovely waitress! The restaurant is kinda small, beautifully designed and very very clean. The kitchen is right there in front you so you can see the whole thing.

I would preferred the bread to be less hard, because it was hard to cut, but still it was great. The tacos and braised beef short rib were delicious. Every dish was really very tasty. < text>
Sweet little spot right across from the plaza. We just finished our half marathon and wine tasting was a part of the package. We crossed the street, were the first people when they opened, had our souvenir glasses on us. Greeted warmly by the host and server, few minutes go by, then we hear a voice shouting, "Is that glass full? Is there wine in that glass?"

After her tantrum she mentioned it was due to a law. Why couldn't she politely come over and say, "I'm sorry, but we're not allowed to have open wine or drinks from other places that we haven't personally served due to the law. We all would have been like, "Yeah, our bad. Sorry about that." Instead got a rude shouting from the bar from 10 feet away.

5 stars for service, -3 for rude person who clearly lacks customer service skills.

Food was meh, wasn't great, wasn't terrible, wasn't memorable. Tiny dishes and the ribs were too salty with no counterbalance or side dishes.<//text>

< user>
115882686977588482521< /user>
< Name>
Paul Rettie</Name>
<Date>1621457232512<//Date><Rate>1<//Rate><review>I'm concerned the quality of the rings and the customer service are not what the company purports it to be so bear this in mind before purchasing a ring you hope will last a lifetime.
I purchased the Hudson Engagement Ring in 2015 and shortly after the matching Hudson Engagement band for my now wife. Initially we were very happy with the whole experience.
Unfortunately approximately 5 years later one of the prongs holding the diamonds became very worn down from rubbing against the matching ring so returned it to San Francisco from the UK. I expected this to fall under the lifetime warranty and Brilliant Earth to accept that there was a design flaw that allowed this to happen so quickly with bands designed to be worn together.
I was promptly phoned and informed that my wife's engagement ring was irreperable and they were willing to offer $119 to scrap her ring (later increased to $228). Certainly not the news you hope for with something that has this much sentimental value but then being told we need to fork out a few thousand pounds on a new one was not welcome.
I did my best to explain that I wouldn't have ever purchased it if I expected the ring ring to last such a short period of time and I certainly do not intent to buy a new ring every 6 years for the rest of our lives.
What are we going from here? Well with my wife not working anymore as she's 39 weeks pregnant, a new ring isn't something we can afford now so shipping it back, still broken, will be the only option.
I'd caution you to learn from my mistake and avoid being in this same situation with your ring in six years time.<//review>< pics>
None</pics>

<UserId.>109007114619306162316< /UserId.><name>Katie Silvester< /name>< date>
1597754514343< /date>
<rating>1<//rating>< Review>
Hi all,

Before I begin explaining our horrific experience with Brilliant Earth, just notice, as you scroll through these reviews, for every bad review, suddenly a flurry of amazing and outstanding reviews follow. I just hope this can reach any person thinking of using (not so) Brilliant Earth.

First and foremost I should not be writing this review; I should not have known that my partner had planned to propose, an engagement is a one in a lifetime experience. We grow up dreaming about the day our significant other is knelt on one knee, displaying a small box, asking to spend the rest our lives together.

My proposal could not have been more different to the above scenario. My engagement, if you will, was calling parcel force asking whether or not my faux diamond bought on Etsy had passed successfully through customs, ensuring it would arrive in time for our wedding on the 25th July.

Rewind a few months prior to this, my now husband was scanning the internet, watching YouTube videos and educating himself on what diamond he should commit a small fortune towards. After finding what he believe to be the one on the Brilliant Earth website, he paid the money and eagerly awaited it's arrival.

Low and behold a FedEx box arrived, but guess what - they had sent the WRONG ring with a diamond half the size of the one he ordered... and so the fun times with Brilliant Earth began.

We got passed from pillar to post and definitely spoke to the same rude lady that was mentioned two posts down, (remember my comment earlier about 1 bad review = 2 great ones...funny that). The lady informed us that the situation was suboptimal (sarcastic tone intended) and as a gesture of goodwill, we were offered $136.72 friends and family discount...... I was dumbfounded, I found the amount, in comparison to the cost of the ring insulting and would have rather not been offered anything. We were then informed the ring would take another 6 weeks to make. The strange thing was, inside the FedEx box we had received was the unique documentation and certificate for the ring that my Husband had purchased, so how were we to know that whatever ‚Äúring‚Äù they were to send us was genuinely the one we bought and also how would they know?

A few phone calls later, we were passed to over to Reuben, who informed us that our ring was in fact sat in the shop and he could get it shipped out to us, even though the previous later had said they didn‚Äôt have it. So, was it there or not?

We got to the point of not caring anymore, we had yet another call with the rude lady who mentioned again that it was to be made and all we cared about now was let‚Äôs just try and get our money back as quickly as possible and be done with this shambles of a company.

After being sent the wrong invoice twice for the ring, (we actually laughed at this as we were at our wits end, could they not do the simplest of tasks) we received the shipping label and packaged the WRONG ring back to the company.

Honestly, we had a glass of prosecco when he was finally refunded. We laugh about it now, and what a debacle it was. Even if a company has 80% good reviews but the negative ones are clearly genuinely unsatisfied customers who have experienced hellish situation beware! Always go with your gut, especially when there is consistency in negative reviews.

I do not want anyone out there to have the same experience as we did. Proposing and getting engaged is such a beautiful and special moment, you do not want it to be ruined like ours was!!

Good luck

Kate< /Review>

< text>
Terrific Custom Design Service ‚Äì Highly Recommended!

We visited the Brilliant Earth San Francisco location about six months ago with the goal to create our uniquely designed engagement ring while at the same time using responsibly sourced materials for every element of the ring. Our experience was fantastic from beginning to end and we cannot express how happy we are with their service and our custom designed engagement ring.

We met with Lauren, who was incredibly patient over the first couple of meetings as we didn‚Äôt really have all the details of the ring‚Äôs features figured out. Lauren‚Äôs expertise and help in selecting the center stone with the exact attributes was invaluable. We never ever felt pressured and the options of center diamonds she sourced for us to look at was amazing. Lauren and her custom ring designer Omar also provided us with an initial design sketch, which was invaluable for us to visualize what our design would look like.

Once we settled on our center stone, Lauren and her team were off to find the matching accent stones and then Omar prepared the final sign off CAD drawings. After a few more custom tweaks the ring was being manufactured (using recycled white gold) and the result was more than incredible ‚Äì more beautiful and stunning as all of the details we had looked at in the months prior.

Thanks again to Lauren, Omar and everyone else at Brilliant Earth for all their help and support in guiding us through the process of designing and finalizing our engagement ring. Your patience and insights were greatly appreciated and led to a truly unique and stunning ring.

Everyone at Brilliant Earth has a very special place in our relationship and we enthusiastically recommend your services!</text>

He doesn't solve anything...he just apologizes and does not relay to the repair or marketing team that the customer is rightfully distressed and unhappy with this entire process...and when the customer finally backs down and says "fine use our insurance and fix the ring, we will continue to leave our reviews"....they decide that the best option is to REFUSE SERVICES TO FIX THE RING....unless we sign an NDA....What they don't realize is when you've put someone through distress for 3 months that doesn't make someone "back down" and WANT to sign an NDA...  To ultimately tell the customer that they're refusing services because they felt "attacked" when REALLY it seems that ultimately the just want us to sign the NDA...that's a VERY sketchy business.

No business will last if they continue to make cheap products, then determine it's a "wear and tear issue" if the ring has been worn for more than 3 months (thus falsely advertising a "lifetime warranty"). No business will last if they infuriate people never admitting to making faulty products and trying to milk insurance money. No business will last if they continue to hide honest reviews by refusing service to customers that dare to tell the truth and take the time to make sure that this company practices ETHICALLY. I don't even want them to e-mail or call back saying that they can repair the ring...this isn't about that. It's about making sure that customers understand that making such a big purchase from this company is a horrible mistake. Yes their showrooms and customization are amazing and their sales staff are incredible people. However, once you make that big purchase...they treat you like dirt.  They are condescending, take forever to return your calls/e-mails, and then ultimately just look out for themselves instead of their customers/the customer experience. I worked with Brilliant Earth over the summer to do a custom engagement ring for my fiance, who had requested a lab-grown stone. <Text>After purchasing an engagement ring, I took the ring to a GIA gemologist for an insurance appraisal. The appraisal was alarmingly lower than the color and clarity rating which Brilliant Earth had provided and advertised. I considered the appraisal was possibly an outlier, so I took the ring to a second GIA certified gemologist for an insurance appraisal. I have now taken the ring to five independent GIA gemologists and found Brilliant Earth had misrepresented and inflated the gemological rating. On average, the color rating was at least one scale lower and the clarity was at least two scales lower than what was advertised and sold to me. I addressed the issue with Brilliant Earth and they informed me 30 days had passed and they could do nothing to help.

As a first time buyer, I feel my good faith has been completely violated and inexperienced buyers should be extremely cautious when buying from Brilliant Earth.< /Text>< UserId.>

Michelle H<//user_name>
<Time>1366782720114<//Time><Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
I was very pleased to come across the company Brilliant Earth. After ruminating for months on what to do for a diamond, I was extremely pleased to see their product range & commitment to ethical practices. I wanted an ethical diamond, and so many sellers are quick to state that they offer 'conflict-free' stones, without any explanation or details to validate this. Brilliant Earth has lots of information on their site to educate you about selecting a stone, and well as detailed reports on the sourcing of their product. Plus the site had rave reviews and loads of credibility with the wedding industry, which made me feel better about purchasing online.

I had my heart set on a cushion cut diamond, but also was interested in the lab created stones. Since no stock was available online, the rep Jonah offered to do a gemstone search for me & see if he could source one. He got back to me & was able to provide all the specs on the stone, as well as a certificate of appraisal. He had one of their senior gemologists grade the cut of the stone (ideal!), since this was omitted on the report. I was very satisfied with the service I received & am excited to get the stone set. I will be telling everyone about where I got the stone from because I feel Brilliant Earth's product, selection, and service was exceptional.</review>

Vivian Chen<//username>
<Time>1526494524085<//Time><Rating>4</Rating>< Text>
This is downtown! Check for any protests/marches before you go or else you will get trapped in the city.

Parking is hard/expensive! Look up parking before you go!

MAKE SURE TO HAVE AN APPOINTMENT! No casual browsing here.

Brilliant Earth is on an upper floor of a building, so check in at the front desk and then take an elevator up!  The security is high, they buzz you into the lobby and then buzz you into the showroom if you want to use the bathroom you have to leave and get buzzed back in!

The consultants were nice. But, you will only get an hour with them and another consultant may have clients there while you are in the showroom. They are very strict about their times and appointments.

The consultants will guide you through various diamond styles and types. ie the 4Cs and lab created and ethically mined. As well as insurance policies and sizing!

They even showed us three different loose diamonds of with differing 4Cs which I thought was cool!

I felt like the consultant sped through choosing the setting, but I got a good view of the variety of styles.

I think it is a great place to start looking and educated, but I would consider looking at other places before buying the diamond!

NO PRICE NEGOTIATING OR HAGGLING HERE.</Text>

<user_name>Jessica McClintic< /user_name>< review>
I could not image a worse experience for my engagement ring. I fell in love with the ring online, and told my then boyfriend about it. I REALLY wish I would have just taken a photo of the ring for a local jeweler to make for me. Even though I had my ring size measured, the salesman convinced my boyfriend to go for a larger size. "It's easier to downsize the ring than upsize" is what he was told. But what he didn't tell him is that I would have to ship my ring off for a month to get it resized. 6 days after I got the ring back, a band diamond FELL OUT. As upset as I was, I agreed to have it shipped off for another month. When I finally got it back--it looked off. The diamond they replaced was slightly smaller than the original and it made the band look uneven. I took it to the showroom where the lady measured the diamonds and confirmed it was smaller. She advised we send the ring back yet again and request the ring be remade. She warned that the company would probably deny our request and that we should threaten to return the ring in order to get it approved. And that's exactly what happened. They didn't want to remake the ring and that's when we had the displeasure of dealing with Mary Pat in Chicago. She wanted us to sign a non-disclosure agreement that basically said the ring would be re-made one last time, as-is (at the company's quality discretion) and that we could not tell anyone about our experience. Up until that point, the quality had not been satisfactory so we did not agree to the terms. Why would we trust the company to do a good job when we no longer had any means to get them to help us? We really wanted a jeweler that we could develop a relationship with--one that would be proud of his work and make quality pieces, and this was just the opposite. As much as I loved the ring, I couldn't help but notice the imperfections every time I looked at it.  We decided to request a refund and start over. As frustrating as the process had been up to that point, it got ten times worse. Mary Pat was unable to send more than one e-mail a day, promised to follow up on certain days and then didn't, disappeared for awhile without any response due to an illness, and was just constantly delaying any progress to come to a resolution with the common reply being "policy" reasons. "Policy" stated that we couldn't return the ring because it had been more than 30 days. But how can that be when they had the ring almost the whole time? Then we agreed to just get the main diamond sent back loose, and BE keep the band. They sent another non-disclosure agreement that again said we can't share our story, we would get the diamond back, and the refund for the band--but not taxes and insurance paid on the band. When my fianc√© asked why we wouldn't get the full refund, they again stated it was policy about the 30 day limit. "We can't give you the full money back, but we can give you earrings or a bracelet instead" was Mary Pat's response. When we told them to forget the deal and just send us back the ring, they sent us an amended NDA and it included returning the taxes and insurance. We were beyond done at the BS they were pulling with us at every attempt to rectify the situation. Companies involved with something as important as this piece of jewelry should not be able to get away with such terrible customer service. We ended up contacting the showroom and having them reach out to their San Francisco location to just send the ring back. We didn't even want to ask Mary Pat (the "top of the top" customer service expert) for fear of what "policy" restriction that would follow. I got the ring back in the mail yesterday, 9/6/18. We had been dealing with this since May. PLEASE PLEASE PLEASE learn from my mistake and take your hard-earned money to someone who actually cares about their customers and the quality rings they create.<//review>

7/3/14 update from  1 star to 4.  .....

Management got involved:) I got a conflict free diamond that matched my original specification, with a discount, and my ring arrived on time!

Hi,

I lost 2 weeks with Brilliant Earth, at the end of which I had no ring and had to reschedule my planned proposal.  Like many, I chose brilliant earth because of their mission: ethical diamonds.  It really pains me to write a poor review.

After purchase, I got a call from a rep who said the diamond I selected had an imperfection and they were working on replacing it.  I said ok, but please keep the price and l/w ratio constant and deliver it no more than 4 days after promised date. She said no prob.

Couple days later I got  another call asking whether I would take a diamond from an unknown source.  Really!? I declined since the reason I chose brilliant earth was because the diamonds were ethically sourced.

Several days later (10 days from my purchase date) I got another call. Rep said perfect diamond finally found that match criteria of diamond I originally purchased.  I was super excited. <response>None<//response><Review>Buying my fiance's engagement ring through Brilliant was a fantastic experience. I knew that I wanted to have an ethically sourced ring for my fiance and began researching different companies that used ethical practices. Brilliant Earth was by far the most popular and top rated ethically sourced jewelry company. I did more research into the company and found out that they were perfect in every way: ethically sourced diamonds, they use recycled precious metal, they use wood from a sustainable tree farm for their ring boxes, and create beautiful jewelry while keeping such high standards. It was decided then: I would not consider any other jeweler than Brilliant Earth.
But then my fiance (girlfriend at the time) sent me a photo of the ring she really liked and Brilliant Earth did not have a ring similar to this design in their inventory. Still determined I contacted Ryan Atlas, the Senior Custom Designer at Brilliant Earth, and discussed with him about developing a custom ring for her. This task seemed daunting and scary for me at the time, especially since I live in Missouri and they are based out of California,  but everything fell into place. He reassured me that Brilliant Earth could recreate the ring in the picture and actually make modifications to it better suit my fiance. So I took a leap of faith and started the design process. I can say that was best decision I could have made during the engagement process.
Everything thing went so smoothly. To begin with, I had no knowledge of jewelry, or diamonds and Ryan stepped through every detail that goes into an engagement ring. I learned all about cut, clarity, color, and carat, and felt like I made an intelligent decision after all of the help Ryan gave me. The design process was also a neat experience. During the design process they send you a CAD rendering of the ring before they make it; so you really have a great visual on the ring to make any changes before it becomes permanent. I only made one minor change and they began building the ring for me.
Ryan kept me updated throughout the design process and calmed any nerves that I had about buying a custom ring over the phone. When the ring was completed (which was about week quicker than they anticipated, Ryan hand picked the ring box that had the most character, and sent it my way! I received it the NEXT day, and could not believe my eyes. It was so beautiful and exceeded every expectation that I had for the ring.
Finally the most important part: was the fiance happy with the ring? She ABSOLUTELY loved it. We both could not be any happier.
I would HIGHLY recommend Brilliant Earth for:
Their ethical practices.
The quality of their jewelry.
Their reasonable prices.
EXCELLENT customer service.

I ordered a diamond in an 18K White Gold Reverie setting from Brilliant Earth in March 2015. Out of the box, my fianc√© and I were initially impressed with our purchase. 10 days later we decided the setting needed to be resized.  We returned the ring and it was returned to us promptly following resizing.

Our positive experience ended upon having the ring returned to us. My fianc√© wore her ring for just 10 days before her diamond was lost while getting ready for school; she looked down to discover one of the prongs in the setting was bent and the diamond was missing. After an exhaustive search of the house, we were unable to locate our stone. Brilliant Earth offered to inspect the setting for manufacture defects.

Before returning the setting to Brilliant Earth, we had their setting evaluated by two local independent jewelers. Both jewelers indicated that the setting was poorly designed (the diamond was too large for the structure of the setting) and had concerns about the quality of the white gold used.

Brilliant Earth performed their own assessment of the setting and determined there were no problems, despite the opinions we had received from other jewelers. Over the course of several weeks, my fianc√© and I debated the issue with one of Brilliant Earth‚Äôs customer service staff. Why on earth would I choose to spend MORE money on their products?!?!

We found that Brilliant Earth claims to stand on high ground regarding sourcing of diamonds and providing quality jewelry. In reality, we found Brilliant Earth to deliver inferior, weakly designed products, and then offer nothing but costly replacements when something goes wrong. Take your money elsewhere! You and your fianc√© will be much happier.</text>

<text>I ordered the "Platinum Sapphire Fancy Halo Ring" for my recent engagement over Easter. I stumbled across Brilliant Earth through Google, since I was trying to find a specific style online, as it was hard to find something in the local jewellery stores.

I was immediately attracted to this design that I ended up choosing, it seemed to be exactly what I was after. Of course there was some trepidation - especially as a poor student I felt it was risky spending a rather large chunk of my money online. However, I spent some time seeking out as many independent reviews of Brilliant Earth as I could. The vast majority of them allayed my worries, and the few negative reviews were mostly revolving around issues during the customisation process - but since I was ordering a standard design this was not of concern to me.

I noticed that the images in their catalogue were computer renders rather than actual photographs of products - they do also have photos of recently purchased rings as well as photos that customers send in as testimonials. I was able to find enough photos of similar rings to the one I was after to be satisfied that the real thing would indeed resemble the catalogue image.

Once I started the enquiry process, I quickly received an email from Jonah, who was the staff member I ended up interacting for the majority of the time. He was always friendly and patient in his responses to my questions.

When I committed to purchase, everything was dealt with reasonably quickly. There was a small mistake where they sent me an invoice for the white gold variant rather than the platinum one I was after, but this was quickly rectified.

Once the payment processed, their claim was that manufacturing would be completed within 2 weeks - and so it was. Their estimates for shipping were also accurate (3-5 business days).

I live in New Zealand, and do not fall under the free shipping agreements, but I only ended up paying NZ$80 for express FedEx shipping. FedEx contacted me in advance to arrange customs clearance (and the rather expensive GST+tariff payment!) and it was delivered to me on the morning that they told me it would be.

When I actually got it, the ring looked amazing in real life, much better even than the rendered image (see my uploaded pictures). It also came in a rimu box (a New Zealand wood) which is a nice touch.

Needless to say, my now-fiancee loved the ring and is extremely pleased to finally have it on her finger!< /text>< pictures>

<Rate>1<//Rate><review>Bought my wife's wedding set from Brilliant Earth and have this updated review.
Engagement ring was 18K Yellow Gold Petite Shared Prong Diamond Ring and her wedding ring was a Petite Shared Prong Diamond Ring.

Look: 5/5 - Open the box look, sparkle, and shine was great, this ring looked incredible, especially after it had just been cleaned.

Design: 0/5 - This is about where the good things to say about the ring stop. My wife lost a stone out of her wedding band after only 4 months of normal wear (she works in an office). We took the ring to two independent jewelers to have it evaluated and they both criticized the shared prongs. They said they were to close together to be effective and the small diamonds in the bands were mis-sized so some were too big, essentially pushing the prongs apart making it easy for one to fall out. One jeweler said that 17 other of the 30-odd diamonds were loose and the prongs needed to be tightened, the other jeweler said that 18 were and showed us a few that were visibly loose to the naked eye. We sent the ring back to BE and they said there were absolutely no problems with the ring or design and would not honor their "Lifetime" warranty on defects, the ring was functioning as designed. They would replace the diamond for $250 and tighten one set of prongs that they said could be an issue, no thank you. Had a local jeweler do them all for less and a replacement stone was only $25, also conflict free.
A month later the engagement ring lost a stone and I complained to BE again, they basically told me they couldn't do anything and I was out of luck. Ended up having the ring melted down and remade by a reputable jeweler.

Center Diamond: 5/5 - Still gorgeous, even through all the problems. Local jeweler confirmed the specs on the cert.

Gold: 3/5 - Nice yellow gold color. The center stone holder is 14k for strength and I wish the other prongs would be as well. 18k is too soft and makes the shared prongs too loose, too soon.

My ring: 5/5 - I also bought my 5mm 18k Yellow gold band from BE as well, after two years it has held up good. Comfort fit is comfortable and easy to get on and off. Took advantage of their one free resize and that worked good.

Sales staff: 5/5 Worked with Ryan Stauffer and Jonah Hugg in ordering the rings. They were both very professional and helpful. nothing negative to say about either of them.

Customer service: 1/5 - This is where problems start again. I tried to voice my concerns with the customer service manager Sharon Dziesietnik a few times and kept getting the same response. They made it very clear that they saw no problems with the rings and said the other two jewelers were trying to get my money from me. Now I may have believed her if it weren't for the ring losing another stone a month later and me being able to see visibly loose stones. They wouldn't return the ring, admit fault, or fix anything I was complaining about (new prongs) and basically said my wife shouldn't wear the ring. Examples of when not to wear the ring taken from my notes on conversation with Sharon; sleeping, showering, biking, yoga, or even playing with kids. I can understand some, but these examples cover a big percentage of our lives. Had the feeling that they just thought my wife was dumb and couldn't handle the ring.

Resolution: Had no resolution with the customer service department and as a result had to pay over $1500 to have the rings remade into a quality product. My wife very much enjoys her new ring from Johnson Jewelers and has had it for over 9 months now with zero problems with the same small and large stone and similar style. If you're reading this considering BE for your engagement ring purchase... do not walk, RUN to your closest, local, reputable jeweler and buy a good product that they will stand behind.<//review>< pictures>

We had the most awful experience with Brilliant Earth and while we were patient and willing to walk away or forgive for adequate compensation...they did neither!

I called Brilliant Earth about my idea for a custom engagement ring.  I wanted my and my fiance's birthstones on the leaves instead of all diamonds. They said they would no problem delivering that day and could probably get it to me sooner.  They subsequently GUARANTEED delivery for that date which I thought was wonderful.

On their website they state that they have a commitment to quality and excellence and let me just say that its an outright lie.  You can say everything you want but if your actions don't match it, then it's not true.

Save yourself the heartache and money and purchase from one of the many other conflict-free providers....99% of all diamonds in the world now follow UN's Kimberely Process.

< text>
I really like Wendy's. Always good food for what it is. However often the workers are kind of rude or short and don't answer simple questions or requests. Several times they have forgotten parts of my meal then when I went back to let them know they would not help me. In the past I have had language problems as well and I wasn't sure if it was sincere or a ploy to get me to accept the order they gave me and go or they don't speak English well enough to take an order or correct a mistaken order. Sometimes they seem so annoyed when I have to tell them I only needed one meal not 2 or 1 of something not 4. But even if it isn't what I wanted. I love Wendy's. So inspite of incompetence and rude employees. I have to give 3 stars where that same experience at any other fast food would be 1 star.< /text>
